 is the first book to connect Yorkshire tweeds to the fashion system. Written in lively, accessible prose, this book will appeal to anyone who works in fashion or who wears fashion. There is nothing like it – and it will raise the bar for historical studies of global fashion. Here you’ll find intriguing stories about a tweed theft from the Leeds Coloured Cloth Hall, debates on tariffs and global trade, the battle against synthetic fibres and the reinvention of British tweeds around heritage marketing. You won’t be bored.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aFashionxHistory. 0aTextile industryzEnglandzYorkshirexHistory. 4aManchester Digital Textbooks. 7aDESIGN / Fashion & Accessories.2bisacsh  aAbraham Moon and Sons.  aBritish.  aHistory of design.  aHistory of textiles.  aLuxury brand.  aWoollen cloth.  aYorkshire.  adesign and innovation.  afabrics.  afamily capitalism.  afashion.  aglobal.  amarketing.  atweed.1 aBlaszczyk, Regina Lee, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb40uhttps://doi.org/10.7765/978152615708940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781526157089423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781526157089/original  aGBV-deGruyter-alles